			<h1>
				<a href="http://werblog.com/2013/08/teaching-and-performance/" title="Teaching and Performance" rel="bookmark">Teaching and Performance</a>
				<i class="comment-bubble">22</i>
			</h1>

			<div class="post-footer">
				2 Aug 2013 &nbsp;&nbsp;| <a href="http://werblog.com/category/education/">Education</a>
				
			</div>

			<div class="post-bodycopy cf">
				<p><strong>Teaching is hard. Â </strong>Some people are naturally good at it, and others are naturally quick at developing good teaching skills. Â For most of us, though, figuring out how to teach effectively is a real challenge.</p>
<p>As a professor, teaching is a central aspect of what I do for a living. Â I&#8217;m deeply committed to teaching well. Â And today, social and technological developments are changing the context of teaching and learning in significant ways. Â So we have an obligation to rethink what we do in light of the new environment. Â Yet I find it hard to talk about teaching with others, at least in the university context that I&#8217;m in.</p>
<p>So I&#8217;m trying something new. Â I&#8217;ll post some thoughts in the hope of generating a conversation. Â <strong>I welcome your thoughts and input.</strong></p>
<p>The starting point for me is that teaching and performance are connected, but distinct. Giving a spellbinding lecture is performance. Â It may be good teaching or bad teaching. Â It has the advantage (most likely) of getting students to show up, pay attention, and perhaps remember something of the experience for a long time. Â All of those are correlated with good teaching. Â They aren&#8217;t themselves teaching. Think of a brilliant actor on stage or a great episode of a TV show. Â You wouldn&#8217;t call that teaching. It&#8217;s performance. Â You might learn something by watching, but the quality of the performance doesn&#8217;t necessarily indicate the quality of the learning. (And yes, I know that movies and games and other things can beÂ <em>designed</em> to teach &#8212; I&#8217;m a gamification expert, after all! I&#8217;m talking about the normal ones designed primarily to entertain.)</p>
<p>Performance is an input; teaching is an output. Â You can measure performance at the source, but you can only measure teaching at the receiver, which in this case is the student. As a consequence, performance is much easier to see than teaching. Any observer can see it. You can even see it by watching a recording. Â It exists, at least in part, outside of the course. Â Teaching doesn&#8217;t.</p>
<p>This distinction seems obvious to me, and yet most people I talk to seem to confuse performance and teaching. Â And that&#8217;s a problem. Â If we reward and encourage performance, we may not actually be encouraging good teaching. Â In fact, we may redirect effort away from it, toward things that don&#8217;t necessarily advance learning. Â This isn&#8217;t a new problem, or an unfamiliar one. Â Basically every text on teaching in higher education published in recent decades criticizes the lecture and the content-delivery emphasis it promotes. Â But the emphasis on performance is a particular problem in this age of MOOCs.</p>
<p>MOOCs make performance even more visible, while hiding teaching further. Â Now the performances are available to anyone in the world through online video, and directly viewed by tens of thousands of eyeballs in the course. Â It&#8217;s easy to compare good performers and bad performers side-by-side. Â And the pre-recorded lecture structure (with the dominant xMOOC approach) removes the interactivity that&#8217;s present even in most in-person &#8220;lecture&#8221; courses, as well as the distraction of sitting in a room with other students. Â The MOOC experience is just you the student, and the instructor on stage. Â And students can vote with their clicks to a greater extent than in a university setting, rewarding the brilliant performers with larger numbers.</p>
<p>None of this is necessarily a bad thing. Â In many ways, it&#8217;s a very good thing. Â To be clear, I&#8217;m a proponent of MOOCs. Â I think they can provide tremendous potential benefits for education, in many contexts. And I&#8217;ve taught a largeÂ <a href="https://www.coursera.org/course/gamification">MOOC</a>, twice. In many ways that makes it easier for me to see the dangers they also create. Â We need to view MOOCs as opportunities for experimentation, not magical solutions. Â And among other things, we need to push back on our natural tendency to view their pedagogical effects purely from the standpoint of performance.</p>
<p>So here&#8217;s my personal problem. Â I feel pretty confident that I&#8217;m good at performance. Â I do a great deal of public speaking. I get plenty of positive feedback on my ability to convey concepts in an engaging way. Â And my Gamification MOOC attracted a high number of students, very strong engagement/completion numbers, and great anecdotal responses. Â All well and good. Â In fact, those are things I&#8217;m proud of. Â Yet they tell me little or nothing about how to teach effectively. Â And the support resources I&#8217;ve found for improving teaching are really geared more toward improving performance. Â I suspect that most university professors, having gone through PhD programs, are less comfortable with performance than teaching. Â I&#8217;m the opposite.</p>
<p>Most of my teaching in my &#8220;day job&#8221; as a professor is in relatively small (20-70) classes, on topics that don&#8217;t emphasize mastery of formal concepts. Â The students need to interact, and they need to apply knowledge. Â I can&#8217;t get away with just performing.</p>
<p><strong>So here&#8217;s the question I keep coming back to: how do I judge success?</strong> Â How can I figure out what&#8217;s good teaching, not just good performance? Â Because until I can answer that question, I find it immensely difficult to feel any sense of satisfaction in what I&#8217;m doing.</p>
<p>Good teaching means that students are learning. Â But that&#8217;s just rephrasing the question. Â How do I know if students are learning? Â I can see how it might be possible to answer that question in subjects where there&#8217;s a well-developed, structured set of concepts that students need to master, generations of students have mastered, and instructors have seen students master time and again. Â I don&#8217;t teach anything like that. Â Any bar I set seems arbitrary: I&#8217;m just making up a target for students to hit. Â It doesn&#8217;t tell me if I&#8217;m doing well or poorly as a teacher.</p>
<p>I think if I can develop a better answer to this question, it will make me more effective as both a classroom teacher and a MOOC instructor. Â And it will help me understand where I can use the MOOC to enhance my in-person course on the same subject. Â This is the benefit and the danger of the &#8220;flipped classroom&#8221; notion: it separates teaching and performance to a large extent. Â If the students watch the performance on video at home the night before, what they experience the next day in the classroom had better be teaching. Â <strong>That&#8217;s a scary thought.</strong></p>
<p><em>Am I looking at this the right way? Â For those of you who teach, how do you decide what constitutes success in a course? What resources were helpful to you in answering that question? Â </em></p>

				
